# A baseline .gitignore for any project a coding assistant works in.
# Copy the parts you need. The two commented sections are the ones that
# actually bite people, so read those before deleting anything.

# Regenerable. Reinstall from a lockfile instead of committing.
node_modules/
.venv/
venv/
__pycache__/
dist/
build/
.next/
.turbo/
coverage/
*.log

# Live session and credential state
**/browser_profile/
**/Cookies*
*.sqlite*
**/auth_info.json

# Secrets. Never commit a real value.
.env
.env.*
secrets*
*.pem
*.key
id_rsa
id_ed25519

# Negations must come AFTER the rule they undo, because the last matching
# rule wins. These two files are meant to be committed: they carry names
# and instructions, never values.
!.env.example
!secrets.template.md

# ── The trap that silently untracks your assistant's configuration ──
# A bare `.claude/` line here would also ignore everything you authored
# inside it, and a fresh clone would lose the lot with no warning. If you
# want to ignore local state but keep the authored parts, ignore the
# directory then negate each authored subdirectory, both the directory
# itself and its contents:
#
# .claude/*
# !.claude/agents/
# !.claude/agents/**
# !.claude/skills/
# !.claude/skills/**
# !.claude/commands/
# !.claude/commands/**
# !.claude/rules/
# !.claude/rules/**
# !.claude/wiki/
# !.claude/wiki/**
# !.claude/settings.json
#
# Verify with: git check-ignore -v .claude/agents/some-agent.md
# It should print nothing.

# Editor and OS detritus
*.bak
*.orig
*~
*.swp
.DS_Store
